<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>{{ title }}</title>
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/stylesheets/style.css" />
    <script type="application/ld+json">
      {%- include "../public/tropy.jsonld" -%}
    </script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <header>
      <div class="container">
        <h1 class="brand"><a href="/">
          <img class="tropy-icon hidden-xs" src="images/tropy-icon-small.svg" width="36" height="32" alt=""><!--
          --><span class="brand-title">Tropy</span></a>
        </h1>
        <nav class="header-nav">
          <a href="#">Blog</a><!--
          --><a href="https://github.com/tropy/tropy"><img src="images/mark-github.svg" width="32" height="32" alt="GitHub"></a>
        </nav>
      </div>
    </header>
    <main>
      <div class="jumbotron">
        <div class="container">
          <img class="tropy-icon" src="images/tropy-icon-large.svg" width="288" height="248" alt="Tropy">
          <p class="lead">Photo management<small>for researchers and archivists</small></p>
          <button class="btn btn-lg btn-primary">Download</button>
          <p class="mobile-hint visible-xs-block">Tropy is a desktop application. Check back on your desktop computing device to download a copy.</p>
          <hr class="visible-xs-block">
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="container">
        <div class="row page-section" id="tropy-at-a-glance">
          <div class="col-sm-12 col-lg-10 col-lg-offset-1">
            <h1>Tropy at a glance</h1>
            <p class="lead">Take control of your research photos with Tropy, a tool that shortens the path from finding archival sources to writing about them. Spend more time using your research photos, and less time searching for them.</p>
            <h2 class="visually-hidden">Main features</h2>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="col-sm-4 main-feature">
                <img src="images/maze.svg" width="260" height="260" alt="Maze">
                <h3>Wrangle your <span class="second-line">photos</span></h3>
                <p>Organize your photos so they're <strong>easy to find</strong>, <strong>easy to edit</strong>, and <strong>easy to analyze</strong>.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-4 main-feature">
                <img src="images/bulk-edit.svg" width="260" height="260" alt="Bulk edit">
                <h3>Describe your research</h3>
                <p><strong>Add information</strong> to your photos <strong>individually</strong> or <strong>in bulk</strong> so that you can remember what research you have.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-4 main-feature">
                <img src="images/open-source.svg" width="260" height="260" alt="Open source">
                <h3>Free & <span class="second-line">open source</span></h3>
                <p>Tropy is <strong>free</strong> and <strong>open source</strong> and ships <strong>cross-platform</strong>: it is friends with Mac, Windows and Linux.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <hr>
        <section class="page-section" id="features">
          <div class="row">
            <div class="col-sm-12 col-lg-10 col-lg-offset-1">
              <h2>Fully-featured & tailor-made</h2>
              <div class="row">
                <div class="col-sm-4 col-md-2 col-md-offset-1 feature">
                  <img src="images/document.svg" width="72" height="72" alt="">
                  <p>Group photos <span class="second-line">around documents</span></p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-4 col-md-2 feature">
                  <img src="images/pencil.svg" width="72" height="72" alt="">
                  <p>Annotate your <span class="second-line">records</span></p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-4 col-md-2 feature">
                  <img src="images/tag.svg" width="72" height="72" alt="">
                  <p>Add custom <span class="second-line">tags</span></p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-4 col-sm-offset-2 col-md-2 col-md-offset-0 feature">
                  <img src="images/search.svg" width="72" height="72" alt="">
                  <p>Search your <span class="second-line">collections</span></p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-4 col-md-2 feature">
                  <img src="images/package.svg" width="72" height="72" alt="">
                  <p>Export your <span class="second-line">research</span></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
        <hr>
        <div class="row page-section">
          <div class="col-sm-12 col-lg-10 col-lg-offset-1">
            <h1>About {{ title }}</h1>
            <p class="lead">Bring order to your research photos — use the power of Tropy to organize and describe your research photos so that you can easily find your sources again, whether you return to them after a day or after several years.</p>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="col-sm-6">
                <p>When you return home from an archives trip with hundreds or thousands of research photos, figuring out how to organize them can feel like finding your way out of a labyrinth. Tropy is a desktop application that seeks to bring order to the chaos by providing a common-sense way to organize and describe research photos. Metadata templates in Tropy allow you to easily attach information to your photos, either individually or in bulk. These templates allow you to describe your research down to the photo level, so you don’t have to read an entire folder of material in order to find one piece. </p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-6">
                <p>You can impose order in Tropy in many ways. Photos can be grouped into documents; documents can be grouped into collections or tagged. A notes field allows you to further describe or transcribe your photos. Full-text search allows you to search across every piece of metadata to find what you need. And Tropy’s ability to export to Omeka and Flickr allows you to integrate it into a research pipeline.</p>
                <p>With Tropy, you do the work of source organization one time, giving you a chance to focus on using your sources, not just finding them.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <hr>
        <div class="row page-section" id="team">
          <div class="col-sm-12 col-lg-10 col-lg-offset-1">
            <h1>Team</h1>
            <p class="lead">The team behind Tropy is based at the <a href="http://http://rrchnm.org/">Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media</a> at <a href="https://www2.gmu.edu/">George Mason University</a> in Fairfax, VA. Part of the team contributes from Vienna, Austria. Tropy is funded by the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation.</p>
            <div class="row text-center contributors">
              <div class="col-sm-4 contributor">
                <h3>Stephen Robertson</h3>
                <p>Principal investigator</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-4 contributor">
                <h3>Sean Takats</h3>
                <p>Principal investigator</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-4 contributor">
                <h3>Sylvester Keil</h3>
                <p>Lead developer</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-4 contributor">
                <h3>Johannes Krtek</h3>
                <p>Product designer</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-4 contributor">
                <h3>Abby Mullen</h3>
                <p>Project manager</p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-sm-4 contributor">
                <h3>Jim Safley</h3>
                <p>Metadata specialist</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </main>
